<subsection xml:id="subsec-working-out-compound-proportions-using-the-ratio-method" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Working out compound proportions using the ratio method</title>
    
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What you need</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Ruler
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Paper
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Pencil and eraser
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculator
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Instructions</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                1. Measure the length and width of the following trianngles, A and B, using a ruler.
            </p>
            <sidebyside>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="Triangle1">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        
                        \draw[very thick,blue] (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (3,2) -- cycle;
                        
                        \node [below,fill=green]at (1.5,-0.1) {Triangle A};


                        \draw[very thick,blue] (6,0) -- (12,0) -- (12,4) -- cycle;
                        
                        \node [below,fill=green]at (9,-0.1) {Triangle B};

                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
            </sidebyside>
           
            
            <p>
                2. Record the measurements of the lengths and widths of triangle A and triangle B.
            </p>
            <p>
                3. Calculate the ratio of the lengths and widths of triangle A to triangle B.
            </p>
            <p>
                Example: length ratio = <m>\frac{\text{Length of B}}{\text{Length of A}}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                4. Compare the two ratios. What do you notice about the relationship between the two triangles?
            </p>
            <p>
                5. Share your work with your fellow learners.
            </p>
            
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <alert>Key Takeaway</alert>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\bullet</m> Two quantities in compound proportion increases or decreases in the same ratio.
    </p>
    <p>
        For example, if you have the ratios <m>3:4</m> and <m>6:8</m>, you can set up the proportion as follows:
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\frac{3}{4} = \frac{6}{8}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Cross-multiplying gives you <m>3 \times 8 = 4 \times 6</m>, which simplifies to <m>24</m>. This confirms that the two ratios are equivalent.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\bullet</m> How to work out compound proportions using the ratio method:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Identify the two ratios you want to compare or relate.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Set up a proportion by equating the two ratios.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Cross-multiply to eliminate the fractions.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Solve for the unknown variable, if applicable.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Check your solution by substituting back into the original ratios to ensure they are equal.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A class has <m>8</m> girls and <m>6</m> boys. More students are admitted to the class so that the ratio of girls to boys remains the same. 
            If the new number of boys in the class is <m>12</m>, determine the new number of girls using the ratio method.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            The initial ratio of girls to boys is:
        </p>
        <p>
            
               <me>8:6</me>
               which simplifies to <me>4:3</me>
            
        </p>
        <p>
            Let the number of girls after admission be <m>y</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Since the ratio must remain the same:
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
               <mrow>\frac{y}{12} =\amp \frac{4}{3}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Cross-multiplying gives:
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>3y =\amp 4 \times 12</mrow>
                <mrow>3y =\amp 48</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Dividing both sides by 3:
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>y =\amp \frac{48}{3} = 16</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, the new number of girls in the class is <m>16</m>.
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

    <example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Kipngetich measured the heights of a mango tree and a person in a photo.  
            Their heights in the photo were <m>10</m> cm and <m>5</m> cm respectively.  
            Since the ratio of their actual heights is the same as in the photo, determine the actual height of the mango tree if the personâ€™s actual height is <m>2.5</m> meters. 
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            The photo ratio is <m>10:5 = 2:1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Let the actual height of the tree be <m>h</m>.  
            Then:
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{h}{2.5} =\amp \frac{2}{1}</mrow>
              <mrow>h = 2 \times 2.5 =\amp 5</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, the actual height of the mango tree is <m>5</m> meters.
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

